The Google car in Uganda is a boxy white SUV with square side mirrors.
In Uganda's national parks, the Google car has a black bar on the front of the car.
License plates in Uganda are white in the front and yellow in the back. The back license plate can be square, as pictured, or long.
In Uganda you may see this man holding a gun whilst following the Street View car.
Ugandan soil is typically very red.

Israel.meta: This is Hebrew, a language is spoken in Israel.
This is Hebrew, a language is spoken in Israel.
Israel has yellow license plates, both front and back. They have a blue vertical stripe on the left of their yellow plates.

This Israeli directional signs features Hebrew, Arabic and Latin lettering. Israeli roads are broken into four main categories- each logo denoted by a colour. Blue = national roads, red = inner city roads, green = regional roads, and black = local roads. In this image, the green denotes regional roads and the road number is 352.
Israeli street lights often feature these black and white stripes on their base.

Jordan.meta: The Jordan car is black if you pan down. This contrasts the white car of the UAE.
The Jordan car is black if you pan down. This contrasts the white car of the UAE.

Jordan’s directional signs are blue with white lettering. They sometimes contain just Arabic but on other occasions feature both Arabic and English. Standard highways in Jordan are denoted by a green rectangle and a number in yellow lettering.

Palestine.meta: Palestine has Arabic as its dominant language. Arabic looks similar to calligraphy and many letters have horizontal lines underneath them. This language contrasts Hebrew which is predominant in Israel.

Palestine has Arabic as its dominant language. Arabic looks similar to calligraphy and many letters have horizontal lines underneath them. This language contrasts Hebrew which is predominant in Israel.
Palestine has elongated white plates that help distinguish it from Israel.

Qatar.meta: Qatar features a white truck beneath you, similar to the UAE and Senegal.
Qatar features a white truck beneath you, similar to the UAE and Senegal.
If you look carefully, Qatari plates have a narrow band of maroon on their left. The plates are long and elongated.
Qatari roads are mainly surrounded by these black and white curbs that look like they have been freshly painted.
Signs in Qatar are typically written in both Arabic and English. This includes street signs, stop signs and directional signs.

Tunisia.meta: This dark green Mazda follows the Street View car in central and southern Tunisia- anywhere south of Hammamet. Also note the red and black license plate.
This dark green Mazda follows the Street View car in central and southern Tunisia- anywhere south of Hammamet. Also note the red and black license plate.
This lighter green Toyota follows the Street View car in Tunis and indeed everywhere in the northern part of Tunisia- north of Hammamet.
Tunisia has black plates that are narrow and long.
Roundabouts are common at Tunisian intersections. They often have directional signs around them, providing useful information.
The official language of Tunisia is Arabic however French is also widely spoken and appears on signs alongside Arabic.
Tunisia most commonly uses these metallic wire-style poles as utility poles.
Tunisia’s landscape has a real Middle-Eastern vibe.
Palm trees are common in Tunisia. The architecture is normally white and has Mediterranean elements fused with Middle-Eastern elements. The sky is normally blue in Tunisia.

Turkey.meta: Seeing the letter ‘ş’ or the letter ‘c’ with a hook underneath in a useful way to confirm that you are in Turkey.
Seeing the letter ‘ş’ or the letter ‘c’ with a hook underneath in a useful way to confirm that you are in Turkey.
These bollards are a common sight throughout Turkey and resemble the Australian and Netherlands bollards however they have a slightly fatter rectangle in Turkey.
Ankara is the only city in Turkey to have these unique-looking street signs that feature a curved top-middle section of the sign.
Turkey uses either blue or green coloured directional signs.

Turkey uses a wide range of utility poles. Some of the more recognisable poles have large holes in them. These poles are different to the poles in Romania, Hungary and Poland as they are made out of metal and have larger holes.
Turkey typically has wide roads with undulating land throughout most of the country, including urban areas.
Turkey has these fairly unique red and white road arrows indicating corners.

Turkish kilometre markers are pictured above. The number (sometimes a letter) in the top left corner indicates what road you are on. If you see the letter ‘o’ followed by a number you are on that road, e.g. the o-5 road in this example. If you see just a number in the top left corner, you are on a D road. For example, 360 indicates the road D360.

United Arab Emirates (UAE).meta: If you pan down in the UAE, you will almost always see a white Street View car. This can be an easy way to tell the country apart from Jordan which has a black Street View car.
If you pan down in the UAE, you will almost always see a white Street View car. This can be an easy way to tell the country apart from Jordan which has a black Street View car.
The generation 4 coverage in UEA was taken with this truck. It can only be found in Dubai and Sharjah.

This is Arabic, a language is largely spoken across the middle-east and northern Africa. You can recognise this written language due to its similarity to calligraphy and many of the words having a line underneath them.
Due to the majority of the UAE coverage being centred around greater Dubai, there is often the possibility of seeing the world’s tallest skyscrapers in the background.
The UAE is one of only a few countries in the world to have some black and white striped poles. Although Jordan sometimes has these too however they are much rarer in Jordan.
